comments: Number of bins. Overridden by "binwidth". Defaults to 30.
The width of the bins. If not provided, "bins" is used instead.

Sets transparency.

1= no transparency,

0= maximum transparency
If TRUE removes all cells with 0 counts.

If FALSE (default) make a standard box plot. If TRUE, make a notched box plot.

Notches are used to compare groups; if the notches of two boxes do not overlap, this suggests that the medians are significantly different.
For a notched box plot, width of the notch relative to the body (default 0.5).
If FALSE (default) make a standard box plot. If TRUE, boxes are drawn with widths proportional to the square-roots of the number of observations in the groups.
Length of the whiskers as multiple of interquartile range. Defaults to 1.5.
Used in the calculation of bandwith (standard deviation of smoothing kernel). Bandwidth=bw*adjust
Useful only when working with default bw. Bandwidth=bw*adjust
Smoothing kernel. Defaults to "gaussian".

Number of equally spaced points at which the density is to be estimated. When n > 512, it is rounded up to a power of 2 during the calculations (as fft is used) and the final result is interpolated byapprox. So it almost always makes sense to specify n as a power of two.
The center of one of the bins (prevents the use of "boundary").
A boundary between two bins (prevents the use of "center").
One of "right" or "left" indicating whether right or left edges of bins are included in the bin.
Amount of horizontal jitter.
Amount of vertical jitter.
Draws horizontal lines at the given quantiles of the density estimate.
If TRUE (default), trims the tails of the violins to the range of the data.

If "area" (default), all violins have the same area (before trimming the tails).

If "count", areas are scaled proportionally to the number of observations.

If "width", all violins have the same maximum width.

Indicate an existing function name

You can also create custom function, e.g. :

function(x) quantile(x, 0.95)
For instance: position_dodge(width=0.75)
